<subSubSection id="A4B3EFB8E91EFFB4FF1CFC74FB95FB64" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="EC16BC33E91EFFB4FF1CFC74FB95FB64" blockId="44.[120,1225,225,1223]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
ETYMOLOGY: Patronym for William M. Mann (1886–1960), collector of the 
<typeStatus id="33120291E91EFFB4FBBEFC74FB8AFBAE" box="[1034,1084,1010,1036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">type</typeStatus>
series, myrmecologist, and eventually director of the National Zoo in 
<collectingRegion id="2E6D72D1E91EFFB4FCA9FB91FC1CFB93" box="[797,938,1047,1073]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Washington</collectingRegion>
, D.C. Mann was the sole entomologist on the ill-fated Mulford Expedition, an engaging account of which was provided in the 1926 book 
<taxonomicName id="2BA9C7B0E91EFFB4FE95FBE7FD87FBD9" authority="Waters and Black" authorityName="Waters and Black" box="[289,561,1121,1147]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Apocynaceae" genus="White" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="DEDD6021E91EFFB4FE95FBE7FD87FBD9" box="[289,561,1121,1147]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">White Waters and Black</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the expedition’s guide, Gordon MacCreagh. Mann, aka “the entomologist” in the account, was one of the few intrepid expedition members, and for whom the book was dedicated: “To the bug-hunter, stout companion of the trail.”
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
